- What is if / else?
  if / else is used to make decisions based on conditions.

if age >= 18 {
    fmt.Println("Adult")
}
Curly braces {} are mandatory.

-- if / else
if age >= 18 {
    fmt.Println("Adult")
} else {
    fmt.Println("Minor")
}

--- else if
if marks >= 90 {
    fmt.Println("A")
} else if marks >= 75 {
    fmt.Println("B")
} else {
    fmt.Println("C")
}

**** Boolean Condition Rule (VERY IMPORTANT) ****
Invalid: 
if 1 { }

Valid:
if x > 0 { }
Go does not allow truthy/falsy values.

-- if with Short Statement (INTERVIEW FAVORITE)
if x := 10; x > 5 {
    fmt.Println(x)
}
x exists only inside if.

- Scope of Variables in if
if x := 10; x > 5 {
    fmt.Println(x)
}
fmt.Println(x) // ❌ error

- Nested if
if a > 0 {
    if a%2 == 0 {
        fmt.Println("Even positive")
    }
}

- Multiple Conditions
  if a > 0 && b > 0 {
    fmt.Println("Both positive")
}
Operators:
  && AND
  || OR
  ! NOT

-- Early Return Pattern (BEST PRACTICE)
func check(age int) {
    if age < 0 {
        return
    }
    fmt.Println("Valid age")
}

-- if with Function Call
if err := doWork(); err != nil {
    fmt.Println(err)
}

In Go, if / else is used for conditional execution where the condition must be a boolean expression, braces are mandatory, and short variable declarations can be used inside the if statement.

================================================================================ Switch =====================================================================================

- What is switch?
switch is used to compare one value with multiple cases and execute the matching block.
✔ Cleaner than multiple if-else
✔ No break needed (default behavior)

day := 2

switch day {
case 1:
    fmt.Println("Monday")
case 2:
    fmt.Println("Tuesday")
default:
    fmt.Println("Invalid day")
}

- Important Rules (VERY IMPORTANT)
    No parentheses ()
    break is automatic
    Only one case executes
    default is optional

- Multiple Values in a Case
  switch day {
  case 1, 7:
      fmt.Println("Weekend")
  case 2, 3, 4, 5, 6:
      fmt.Println("Weekday")
  }

- switch with Expression (Condition Switch)
  score := 85
  switch {
  case score >= 90:
      fmt.Println("A")
  case score >= 75:
      fmt.Println("B")
  default:
      fmt.Println("C")
  }

*-*-*-*- switch with Short Statement (INTERVIEW FAVORITE)
  switch x := 10; x {
  case 5:
      fmt.Println("Five")
  case 10:
      fmt.Println("Ten")
  }
x scope → only inside switch

*-*-* fallthrough (TRICKY)
  switch x := 1; x {
  case 1:
      fmt.Println("One")
      fallthrough
  case 2:
      fmt.Println("Two")
  }
o/p One
    Two

fallthrough:
Forces next case to execute
Does NOT check condition again

*-*-*- Type Switch (VERY IMPORTANT)
Used with interfaces.

var x interface{} = 10
switch v := x.(type) {
case int:
    fmt.Println("Integer", v)
case string:
    fmt.Println("String", v)
default:
    fmt.Println("Unknown")
}
✔ Used in generic code

-*-*- Switch Without Condition
switch {
case true:
    fmt.Println("Always runs")
}

-*-*- Nested Switch
switch a := 1; a {
case 1:
    switch b := 2; b {
    case 2:
        fmt.Println("Nested")
    }
}

-*-*- break in switch
switch x {
case 1:
    fmt.Println("One")
    break
}
Rarely needed (break is default)

- Best Practices
  ✔ Use switch for multiple values
  ✔ Avoid fallthrough unless needed
  ✔ Prefer condition switch over long if-else
  ✔ Keep cases small

-*-*- In Go, switch provides a clean way to handle multiple conditions, automatically breaks after each case, supports expression-less switches, and includes type switches for interface handling.










